conomy examines the transformation of Rome's governing elites as a result of changes in the city's economic, political, and spiritual landscape.Palmer explores this shift through the history of Roman political society, its identity as an urban commune, and its once-and-future role as the spiritual capital of Latin Christendom. Tracing the contours of everyday Roman politics, The Virtues of Economy reframes the reestablishment of papal sovereignty in Rome as the product of synergy between papal ambitions and local political culture. More broadly, Palmer emphasizes Rome's distinct role in evolution of medieval Italy's city-communes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChristianity and politicszItalyzRomexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aPapacyxHistoryy1309-1378. 0aPapacyxHistoryy1378-1447. 0aPolitical culturezItalyzRomexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMedieval History, Renaissance History, religious History, documentary culture/practice, urban history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501742385?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501742385423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501742385/original  a978-3-11-061017-8  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2019